Pittsburgh Internet

Internet Connectivty in Pittsburgh

Introduction

In 538's Lots of People in Cities Still Can't Afford Broadband, Clare Malone plots internet subscription rates and connections speeds using FCC and Census data. This notebook seeks to create similar plots for census tracts in the City of Pittsburgh.

Andrew Gaidus' article Creating Web Maps in Python with GeoPandas and Folium and particularly his example Jupyter notebook, served as a template for this notebook.

I plot a choropleth of census tract density per 1000 households of internet connection with service over 200 kbps in at least one direction.

#Import the necessary Python moduless
import pandas as pd
import geopandas as gpd
import numpy as np
from geopandas.tools import sjoin
import folium
from folium.plugins import MarkerCluster
import shapely
from shapely.geometry import Point
import unicodedata
import pysal as ps

Data Prep

In this section I create GeoDataFrames of census tract FCC data and Pittsburgh census tracts to isolate tracts of interest.

Read in Internet Connectivity Data and Create a GeoDataFrame

First I read in a CSV file of Federal Communication Data for 2016 into a Pandas DataFrame. I downloaded the raw data from the FCC Form 477 Census Tract Data on Internet Access Services. Next, I read in a Shapefile of Pittsburgh Census Tracts, which I downloaded from the Western Pennsylvania Regional Data Center Pittsburgh 2014 CDBG Census Tracts. GeoPandas reads a Shapefile directly into Python really easily.

#Read in CSV file specifying date field and encoding. Sort by date
all_connections = pd.read_csv('tract_map_jun_2016.csv', 
                              dtype={'tractcode': object}, 
                              encoding = 'utf-8')
#By setting index seperately, we protect the dtype specification above
all_connections = all_connections.set_index('tractcode')

#Read in CSV file specifying tract codes of interest
pittsburgh_tracts = pd.read_csv('Pittsburgh_2014_CDBG_Census_Tracts.csv',
                        dtype={'STATEFP10': str, 
                               'COUNTYFP10': str, 
                               'STATEFP10': str,
                               'TRACTCE10': str,
                               'GEOID10': str},
                        encoding = 'utf-8')
#Add the FPIS segments to match the FCC tract code
pittsburgh_tracts['tractcode'] = pittsburgh_tracts['STATEFP10'].astype(str) +\
    pittsburgh_tracts['COUNTYFP10'].astype(str) + pittsburgh_tracts['TRACTCE10'].astype(str) 
pittsburgh_tracts = pittsburgh_tracts.set_index(['tractcode'])

#Inner merge data source and specified tracts
result = pd.merge(all_connections, pittsburgh_tracts, left_index=True, right_index=True, 
    how='inner')
print '{} merged tracts'.format(str(len(result)))

138 merged tracts

#Read tracts shapefile into GeoDataFrame
tracts = gpd.read_file('Pittsburgh_2014_CDBG_Census_Tracts.shp')

%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
tracts.plot()

Merge FCC Data with Census Tracts

Then in one line of code, I spatially join census tracts to FCC data. 

#Join result to tracts based on GEOID10
tracts = tracts.merge(result, on='GEOID10')

Ploting the Data

We add a choropleth of census tracts to a Folium basemap. Below, I first create a basemap that is centered in Pittsburgh, and then I add a choropleth on this basemap specifying the Census Tract ID Field as well as the desired field.

#Create PGH basemap specifying map center, zoom level, and using the default OpenStreetMap tiles
internet_map = folium.Map([40.4368, -79.9777], zoom_start = 12)

def add_choropleth(mapobj, gdf, id_field, value_field, fill_color = 'YlOrRd', 
                   fill_opacity = 0.6, line_opacity = 0.2, num_classes = 5, 
                   classifier = 'Fisher_Jenks'):

    #Call Folium choropleth function, specifying the geometry as a the WGS84 dataframe 
    #converted to GeoJSON, the data as the GeoDataFrame, the columns as the user-specified 
    #id field and and value field. key_on field refers to the id field within the GeoJSON 
    #string
    mapobj.choropleth(geo_str = gdf.to_json(), data = gdf, 
                      columns = [id_field, value_field], 
                      key_on = 'feature.properties.{}'.format(id_field),
                      fill_color = fill_color, fill_opacity = fill_opacity, 
                      line_opacity = line_opacity,  
                      threshold_scale = None)
    return mapobj

#Update basemap with choropleth
internet_map=add_choropleth(internet_map, tracts, 'GEOID10','pcat_all')

Display and Save Map

I add Layer Control to the map. Then I save my finished map as an HTML and display it! 

folium.LayerControl().add_to(internet_map) #Add layer control to toggle on/off
internet_map.save('pgh_internet.html') #save HTML
internet_map #display map
